                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d673">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/1575: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-05T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 5, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received October 5—7:53
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>498. In reply to my question based on the Department’s 285, October 4, 6 p.m.,
                    Foreign Office stated that the attitude of British Government reported in my
                    493, October 4, 9 [<hi rend="italic">4?</hi>] p.m., “is based upon legal
                    considerations since no declaration of war exists”. Foreign Office added,
                    however, that the anticipated action of the Council over this week-end or Monday
                    would presumably alter the present status. Since this is all information
                    obtainable today I will again raise the question on Monday.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bingham</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
